{"id":"1610.04469","submitter":"Jon Johnsen","authors":"Jon Johnsen","title":"On the Theory of Type 1,1-Operators","comments":"Doctoral dissertation, updated October 2016 to give the publication\n  data of the work, and to correct the (mainly) mathematical misprints\n  communicated at the defence as well as a few other issues in the text.\n  (Original is available at Aalborg University on\n  http://dx.doi.org/10.5278/53371203).Version 2 just fixed a bad DOI-link","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.5278/53371203","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This dissertation concerns the pseudo-differential operators of type 1,1.\nThese have been known especially since around 1980, when it was shown that they\nplay an important role in the treatment of fully non-linear partial\ndifferential equations. First an account of the historical development in the\narea is given, including fundamental contributions due to G. Bourdaud and L.\nH\\\"ormander in 1988-89, with concise remarks on the authors contributions.\nSecondly a detailed exposition is given of the systematic theory of type\n1,1-operators, based on the general definition of such operators proposed by\nthe author in 2008. This includes an account of how the previous extensions are\ngeneralised hereby. Moreover, the conjecture from 1978 by C. Parenti and L.\nRodino that type 1,1-operators are pseudo-local is proved in this framework. It\nis also analysed how such operators can change the support and the spectrum of\nthe functions they act on. Furthermore, the question of which temperate\ndistributions such operators have in their domains have been extensively\ntreated, and departing from H\\\"ormander's analysis of the operators fulfilling\nthe twisted diagonal condition or, more generally, belong to the self-adjoint\nsubclass, such operators are shown to be everywhere defined. Finally the\nparadifferential splittings and the resulting boundedness in Lp Sobolev spaces,\nand the more general Besov and Lizorkin--Triebel spaces, are amply discussed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 14 Oct 2016 14:03:57 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 20 Mar 2017 09:34:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-03-21"}
